William Unruh (unruh@physics.ubc.ca) wrote:
> interfere.) So you in some sense replace exponential in time by exponential in
> complexity, but all on the same computer rather than on an exponentially large
> number of them. So if the assumption that you can maintain coherence over an
> exponentially large number of terms is right, you gain. That assumption is however
> open to some question.


No it is not.  The exponentially large number of terms is utterly irrelevant
to the (very difficult) problem of maintaining coherence.

Maintaining coherence is only slightly more difficult on a computer with
1024 bits and 10^306 states than on a computer with 512 bits and 10^153
states.


